Due to some of the escalations last week, I put together an ADO program tha=
t looks at tickets that have been commented on but not updated after 30 day=
s (easy to adjust). It produced this list of tickets that I think might be =
of interest to the project managers and team leads. Finding the exact defin=
ition of updating a ticket was tricky since some updates aren't really mean=
ingful and can be triggered without addressing the comments. What are your =
thoughts about how we use something like this to ensure we don't have orpha=
ned tickets result in disconnects?

Here is the current definition:
 Orphaned Ticket Definition: A ticket is flagged as "orphaned" when its mos=
t recent comment (a System.History entry with no accompanying material fiel=
d changes) has had no meaningful   follow-up within the staleness threshold=
 (currently 30 days). A "meaningful follow-up" is any field change that rep=
resents a deliberate human action on the ticket =97 such as changing   the =
state, reassigning it, editing the title or description, updating the itera=
tion/sprint, changing priority, or adding/removing links and attachments. U=
pdates that do not count as a  response include: system bookkeeping fields =
that ADO auto-updates on every save (Rev, Watermark, ChangedDate, ChangedBy=
), BacklogPriority changes (which occur when someone drags  items to reorde=
r them on a board =97 as seen in ticket 61933 where Doug Fish's 1/5/2026 "u=
pdate" was only a board reorder), BoardColumn/BoardColumnDone (auto-set by =
ADO), Kanban board   extension markers (WEF_*), and companion fields that f=
ire automatically alongside a primary change (like Reason, StateChangeDate,=
 ActivatedDate/ActivatedBy, ClosedDate/ClosedBy, and  iteration/area level =
breakdowns).
In short: if the only activity after a comment is board reordering or syste=
m bookkeeping, the ticket is considered orphaned because no one has taken  =
 real action in response to the comment.


Steve Harlow

Vice President of Software Development
